# Config for the zerogex-web-janitor systemd service (nightly cleanup).
# Copy to janitor.env (same dir) and edit. All keys are OPTIONAL — with none
# set, the janitor uses the Makefile defaults. These are read by
# `make janitor-noconfirm` as make variables.
#
#   cp janitor.env.example janitor.env && chmod 600 janitor.env
#
# Do NOT commit janitor.env.

# --- Auth-DB backup retention (SHARED with `make backup-auth`) --------------
# The nightly prune deletes ~/zerogex-auth-backups/auth-*.db.gz* older than
# AUTH_BACKUP_RETENTION_DAYS, but ALWAYS keeps the newest AUTH_BACKUP_KEEP
# regardless of age. The auth DB is Tier-1 (only copy of every account, password
# hash, session, and user->Stripe mapping; RPO ~1h), so the keep floor is a
# safety net: even if backups stall and every archive ages past the retention
# window, the newest AUTH_BACKUP_KEEP survive. Set AUTH_BACKUP_KEEP=0 for the
# raw mtime-only behavior (no floor) as an escape hatch.
# Use an ABSOLUTE path here — under systemd the unit's HOME is /home/ubuntu, but
# do not rely on a bare '~'.
#AUTH_BACKUP_DIR=/home/ubuntu/zerogex-auth-backups
#AUTH_BACKUP_RETENTION_DAYS=30
#AUTH_BACKUP_KEEP=48

# --- Next.js build cache ----------------------------------------------------
# Deleted wholesale each night and regenerated on the next build. This is ONLY
# the cache subdir — never the built .next output. Path is relative to the
# service WorkingDirectory (/home/ubuntu/zerogex-web).
#NEXT_CACHE_DIR=frontend/.next/cache

# --- npm cache --------------------------------------------------------------
# `npm cache clean --force` runs as this user, never root. The systemd unit
# already runs as ubuntu, so this only matters if you invoke the target via sudo
# by hand; then the recipe drops to APP_USER for the npm step.
#APP_USER=ubuntu
